{"h": 1471, "w": 1290, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 1731, "w": 866, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 1731, "w": 1290, "x": 0, "y": 0}], "height": 1731, "width": 1290}, "sizes": {"large": {"h": 1731, "w": 1290}}, "type": "photo", "url": "https://t.co/IpxA3SPX3t"}, {"allow_download_status": {"allow_download": true}, "display_url": "pic.twitter.com/IpxA3SPX3t", "expanded_url": "https://twitter.com/mikekalilmfg/status/2049993497915117833/photo/1", "ext_media_availability": {"status": "Available"}, "features": {"large": {"faces": []}, "orig": {"faces": []}}, "id_str": "2049993493402025984", "indices": [146, 169], "media_key": "3_2049993493402025984", "media_results": {"id": "QXBpTWVkaWFSZXN1bHRzOgwAAQoAARxzCjiOFwAACgACHHMKOZsXUQkAAA==", "result": {"__typename": "ApiMedia", "id": "QXBpTWVkaWE6DAABCgABHHMKOI4XAAAKAAIccwo5mxdRCQAA", "media_key": "3_2049993493402025984"}}, "media_url_https": "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HHMKOI4XAAAoAOG.jpg", "original_info": {"focus_rects": [{"h": 722, "w": 1290, "x": 0, "y": 292}, {"h": 1290, "w": 1290, "x": 0, "y": 8}, {"h": 1471, "w": 1290, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 2010, "w": 1005, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 2010, "w": 1290, "x": 0, "y": 0}], "height": 2010, "width": 1290}, "sizes": {"large": {"h": 2010, "w": 1290}}, "type": "photo", "url": "https://t.co/IpxA3SPX3t"}]}, "card": null, "place": {}, "entities": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "timestamps": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "quoted_tweet": null, "retweeted_tweet": null, "isLimitedReply": false, "communityInfo": null, "article": null}, {"type": "tweet", "id": "2049956626539417673", "url": "https://x.com/Markullill/status/2049956626539417673", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/Markullill/status/2049956626539417673", "text": ">>>>> PrismaX vs. Tesla, Boston Dynamics, and Others: What's the Fundamental Difference? <<<<<\n\nwhen you hear about robotics, Tesla Optimus, Boston Dynamics Atlas and Figure AI immediately come to mind, but @PrismaXai isnt their competitor. It's a fundamentally different type of company.\n\neveryone builds robots. \nprismax builds the infrastructure for everyone.\n\nTesla, Boston Dynamics, Figure AI and Agility Robotics are all vertically integrated. They design hardware, write software, collect data and train models exclusively for their own products. \n\nTesla uses the AI \u200b\u200binfrastructure from its Full Self-Driving program and the Dojo supercomputer to train Optimus.\n\nTesla's data runs exclusively on Tesla. PrismaX\nPrismaX doesn't build robots. It builds a protocol that everyone can use tesla, boston dynamics, startups and any future company.\n\nAWS Analogy\nBefore Amazon Web Services, every internet company built its own servers. AWS took over all the infrastructure work, allowing companies to focus on their products. \nPrismaX does the same for robotics: centralizing teleoperation, data collection, and quality assessment in a single open protocol.\n\nthe market is growing for everyone\nThe humanoid robot market has grown from a handful of research labs to a global market worth $2.9 billion in 2025. \n\nGlobal investment in robotics exceeded $10 billion in 2025. The more companies build robots, the more data they need. The more valuable the PrismaX infrastructure becomes. \n\nwhy the protocol approach wins\nVertically integrated players compete with each other. PrismaX collaborates with them all. \n\nEvery new robot in the world is a potential client for its dataset. This is a fundamentally different business model: not a winner-takes-all, but an infrastructure that wins along with the industry.", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 0, "replyCount": 2, "likeCount": 8, "quoteCount": 0, "viewCount": 227, "createdAt": "Thu Apr 30 20:58:40 +0000 2026", "lang": "en", "bookmarkCount": 0, "isReply": false, "inReplyToId": null, "conversationId": "2049956626539417673", "displayTextRange": [0, 309], "inReplyToUserId": null, "inReplyToUsername": null, "author": {"type": "user", "userName": "Markullill", "url": "http